    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter today\u2019s slate with **Pete Crow-Armstrong** (80.98) headlining our lineup. Despite the unfavorable #8 spot in the order, his matchup against Sasaki is our strongest point-per-dollar play; the combination of a high-xERA opposing starter (+19% SP skill) and favorable platoon dynamics yields an elite projection that cannot be benched. We are also leaning heavily on the high-floor production of **Junior Caminero** (71.50) and **Trea Turner** (70.16). **Trea Turner** remains the engine of our SB-focused build, and while his projection is slightly hampered by the assumption of a leadoff spot against Bryce Elder, his ceiling remains the highest on the roster. **Kyle Schwarber** (66.62) serves as our primary power threat, boasting an elite 0.402 xwOBA that makes him an essential start despite the lineup pending status.\n\nThe most difficult decision on today\u2019s card was the exclusion of **Victor Scott II** (38.48). While his sprint speed is exactly what the Zebras prioritize, his matchup against Woo is stifling; the combination of a sub-3.30 xERA arm and a bottom-of-the-order assignment suppressed his efficiency score below our 40.0 floor. We opted for the volume of **Hyeseong Kim** (57.38) instead, as the wind-out conditions and the platoon advantage provided a safer path to value. We are monitoring **Gary Sanchez**, **Trea Turner**, **Kyle Schwarber**, and **Pete Crow-Armstrong** closely as their official lineups remain pending. Should these positions shift significantly\u2014particularly if **Trea Turner** is moved out of the leadoff role\u2014we will re-evaluate our pinch-hit strategy, though we remain confident that our depth, including reserves like **Luke Raley**, **Lars Nootbaar**, **Jerar Encarnacion**, **Josh Smith**, and **Luis Pena**, provides adequate coverage. Meanwhile, we continue to hold **Christian Yelich** on the IL, **Carson Benge** due to a rainout, and **Zac Veen** in the minors as we await their return to active status.",
